@NODE login "The login"
You may define 10 different segments for the user when he logs in. Each and
one of them consist of a function and an argument. One the segments should
be the "login"-function. And remember to NOT put any mail handling
functions before the "login"-function. If you do that, I would THINK that
everything goes straight to hell:))
@ENDNODE

@NODE menus "The menu systems"
When the user has bypassed all the 10 login segments he might encounter the
menus. You may define a different menusystem for each and every accesslevel
so that a user with accesslevel 2 will have greater possibilities than a
user with accesslevel 1. You define menus in much the same way as you
define the login sequence.

When you define menus you must also edit descriptions for the items, this
is the only text that will be displayed to the user...

By using the copy-button you may copy the current menu to any other of the 9
menus. Instead of edit all from scratch you can create one basic menu, copy
it and make small changes.
@ENDNODE

@NODE functions "Functions"
There are 12 functions to use in version 2.1 of AmiMUS. In later updates
there will be several more. The functions may be used in the login
sequence, the scriptfiles or in the menus. Click at the funcion to recieve
information about!

	@{"Login              " link funlogin}
	@{"Display text       " link text}
	@{"Display picture    " link picture}
	@{"Quit to DOS        " link quit}
	@{"Play tracker-module" link play}
	@{"Read mail          " link Readmail}
	@{"Write mail         " link Writemail}
	@{"AmigaDOS command   " link AmigaDOS}
	@{"Run AMOS prog      " link Amos}
	@{"System Information " link sys}
	@{"AmiMUSScript       " link script}

All functions may have an ARGUMENT. This is the text/pic etc to use with
the function.

When you define a function as a part of a menu or the login sequence you
may enter FSEL as argument. This will give the user a FileSELector to
chose text/picture etc from. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE script "Scriptfiles
From version 2.1 you may write script-files to use in the login or the
menus. The scriptfiles are normal text-files, written in any editor at all
containing special commands that AmiMUS can understand.

@{"General commands" link general}
@{"Function commands" link fc}
@{"Reserved variables" link vars}

Have a look at the example files to understand more...
@ENDNODE

@NODE general "General commands"
                             General commands

#AmiMUS
The Script file MUST begin with this row, for the interpreter to understand
that it is a AmiMUSscript-file.

#Cls
Clears the screen.

#Title [text]
Displays [text] in a WB3.1-style title bar.

#Wait [action]
Stops the script until [action] happends, it can be one of the following:
1 Waits until a key is pressed
2 Waits until a mouse key is pressed
3 Waits until a key or a mouse key is pressed
If no action is given the interpreter uses action nr 3.

#Print [text]
Prints [text] at screen.
@ENDNODE

#Centre [text]
Centres [text] at screen.

#End
Ends the script...

@NODE fc "Function Commands"
                             Function-commands

#Login
The Login function.

#Display text [text] [FSEL]
The Display Text-function.

#Display picture [picture] [FSEL]
The Display Picture function.

#Quit to DOS
The Quit to DOS-function.

#Play tracker-module [module] [FSEL]
The Play Tracker-module function.

#Read mail
The Read Mail-function.

#Write mail
The Write Mail-function.

#AmigaDOS command [command] [FSEL]
The AmigaDOS command-function.

#Run AMOS prog [prog] [FSEL]
The Run AMOS prog-function

#System Information
The System Information-function.

#AmiMUSScript [script] [FSEL]
The AmiMUSScript function:)
@ENDNODE

@NODE vars "Reserved variables"
AmiMUSscript does not yet support the use of own variables but there are
some reserved variables for you to use. When you use a variable in a
command it is replaced by the string stored in the variable.

$auser		The active user name
$apass		The active user password
$alevel		The active user accesslevel
$users		The number of users
$last		The name of the last user
$mem		All free chip and fast mem
$sysname	The name of the system
@ENDNODE

@NODE sys "System Information"
Displays a LITTLE information about the system. Shows last user, logins all
together and the number of users. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE Amos "Run an AMOS prog"
Should run an Amos prog. Don't trust To much in it though:)
@ENDNODE

@NODE AmigaDOS "AmigaDOS command"
Run any AmigaDOS command. There might be a smart idea to use the Run
command to run the stuff in the background. AmiMUS will otherwise wait
until the program has finished and then return the user to the AmiMUS
screen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE readmail "Read Mail"
This function lets the user read any mail.
@ENDNODE

@NODE writemail "Write Mail"
This function lets the user write mail.

Uses the built-in line-editor as default(just name the editor "int"), but 
may be configured to use an external editor also. But remember that this
doesn't work with any editor. Test a lot:)

The internal editor was VERY improved in version 2.02, since it used to be
a line-editor. Now it's acctually usefull!
@ENDNODE

@NODE play "Play Tracker-module"
Plays any normal tracker-module.

You may define if the module should loop or not.
@ENDNODE

@NODE quit "Quit to DOS"
This funcion quits to AmigaDOS.

You may define if the screen shall fade out, and if there shall be a verify
requester.
@ENDNODE

@NODE funlogin "The login function"
This is the password protected login where the user will be asked for name
and password. 

You may configure the requesters and how many times the system will accept a
login failure before the system locks.

The loginfunction will print all logins to AmiMUS:data/AmiMUS.log. This is a
normal textfile that can be viewed by any textreader. All login attempts
will be registrated.
@ENDNODE

@NODE text "Display text"
This is the textviewer. Prints any normal ASCII text.

You may navigate through the text using the arrowkeys up and down, but it's
more recommended to use PageUp and PageDown at the numeric keyboard.

You finish the reading by pressing 'x'...
@ENDNODE

@NODE picture "Display Picture"
Views any IFF-picture. Waits until the user presses the mouse key or any
key on the keyboard, and then returns to the previous screen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE users "Users"
You may define your users in the main configuration program. Just click at
the gadget "System users: 0". Now the lower half of the screen will switch
to a user editor. Click at "Add User" to add a new user( :) ) or click at
one of the users in the list window to edit him. When you have seleced a
user you may press "Delete" to erase the user.

Most of the functions talk for them self here... Accesslevel can be
anything from 1-9 and it shows wich menusystem the user will encounter when
he reaches the menus!!
@ENDNODE

